    <stitle>AIR COMPRESSOR: HOLSET SS 296 AND QE 296/338 - DISASSEMBLE</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>DISASSEMBLE</title>
        <svcsubsecinfo>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>When it is necessary to remove the cylinder head assembly or any of its parts, the compressor
                        does not need to be removed from the engine if access is available. Some engine or vehicle
                        installations may require removal from the engine to service the head components.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>When any component is serviced or removed from the air system, be sure to set the parking
                        brake and block the vehicle wheels to prevent it from moving while service is being performed.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
        </svcsubsecinfo>
        <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="16">
            <title>SS 296 COMPRESSOR</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Clean and blow dry the top section of the air compressor. Take special care to blow out the
                        groove around the unloader body O-ring groove.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>The unloader valve body is installed with spring tension. It must be removed carefully to
                        avoid personal injury.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Hold down on the unloader valve body and remove the two captive washer bolts and the two
                    flat washers (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401420">Figure 20</hotlnk>). Note the position of the "heavy" flat washers in the
                    unloader body cutouts. Always use new washers included in kits.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401420" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401420" filename="../figg04/G0401420.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 20. Remove Washers</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the unloader body (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401421">Figure 21</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401421" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401421" filename="../figg04/G0401421.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 21. Remove Unloader Body</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the O-Ring seal (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401422">Figure 22</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401422" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401422" filename="../figg04/G0401422.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 22. Remove O-Ring Seal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the unloader compression spring, 3-leg unloader cap and unloader vee seal (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401423">Figure 23</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401423" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401423" filename="../figg04/G0401423.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 23. Remove Unloader Compression Spring</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the intake valve seat (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401424">Figure 24</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401424" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401424" filename="../figg04/G0401424.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 24. Remove Intake Valve Seat</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the intake valve (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401425">Figure 25</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401425" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401425" filename="../figg04/G0401425.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 25. Remove Intake Valve</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the intake valve spring (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401426">Figure 26</hotlnk>). At this point an inspection of the exhaust valve seat
                    should be made. Check for carbon buildup around the small outer holes and the large center hole. If
                    excessive carbon is found, continue with disassembly.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401426" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401426" filename="../figg04/G0401426.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 26. Remove Intake Valve Spring</caption>
                </figure>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">If little or no carbon is seen in the exhaust seat area, then the exhaust valve
                        function should be checked by re-installing the
                        <emph type="bold">intake valve seat</emph>
                        and
                        <emph type="bold">unloader body</emph>
                        with
                        <emph type="bold">bolts and washers only</emph>. This will hold the exhaust seat in place. Then
                        apply shop air to the discharge line of the compressor and check for air leakage at the air
                        intake port and/or the unloader port. If no air leakage is evident, then no further disassembly
                        is needed.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">If air leakage is detected, it indicates a broken exhaust valve spring, exhaust
                        valve or some other leak cause. Continue with disassembly of the head or use exhaust seat puller
                        kit (ZTSE-4362) (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0401427">Figure 27</hotlnk>) to remove the exhaust seat, then remove the
                        exhaust valve, spring and wear washer by hand or with a small O-ring pick. Remove dirt from the
                        exhaust seat cavity using a shop vacuum. Appropriate unloader valve or head repair kit can now
                        be installed.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1"></para>
                    <figure id="f0401427" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0401427" filename="../figg04/G0401427.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 27. Exhaust Seat Puller Kit</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the four hexagon bolts, lock- washers and flat washers (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401428">Figure 28</hotlnk>). Keep them for reuse.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401428" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401428" filename="../figg04/G0401428.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 28. Remove Four Bolts and Washers</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the cover (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401429">Figure 29</hotlnk>). Remove and discard the cover gasket.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401429" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401429" filename="../figg04/G0401429.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 29. Remove Cover</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the cylinder head (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401430">Figure 30</hotlnk>). Clean and keep for reuse. Remove and discard the head
                    gasket
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401430" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401430" filename="../figg04/G0401430.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 30. Remove Cylinder Head</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a press and an air compressor seat removal tool (ZTSE-4363) to remove the exhaust
                    valve seat assembly from the head (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401431">Figure 31</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401431" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401431" filename="../figg04/G0401431.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 31. Remove Exhaust Valve Seat</caption>
                </figure>
                <para>Some models may not require a press to remove the seat. Those models use a seat stem O-ring
                    instead of a press fit. Others have an O-ring in the head. Exhaust seat puller kit (ZTSE-4362) may
                    be used without removing the compressor head.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the O-ring seal from the exhaust valve seat (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401432">Figure 32</hotlnk>). Some models also have an O-ring on the stem. If there
                    is one, remove it and use a new one, at assembly, from the Maintenance or Service kit.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401432" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401432" filename="../figg04/G0401432.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 32. Remove O-Ring Seal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the exhaust valve (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401433">Figure 33</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401433" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401433" filename="../figg04/G0401433.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 33. Remove Exhaust Valve</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the exhaust valve spring (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401434">Figure 34</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401434" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401434" filename="../figg04/G0401434.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 34. Remove Exhaust Valve Spring</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the wear plate (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0401435">Figure 35</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0401435" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0401435" filename="../figg04/G0401435.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 35. Remove Wear Plate</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
